e="paperitopens">{{cite web|url=http://archive.jta.org/article/1953/09/23/3037140/israels-first-international-exhibition-opened-in-jerusalem|title=Israel’s First International Exhibition Opened in Jerusalem|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> It lasted for 22 days, closing on 14 October. It was visited by 600,000 people.<ref name="paperclose">{{cite web|url=http://archive.jta.org/article/1953/10/16/3037370/israels-first-international-exhibition-closes-visited-by-600000|title=October 16, 1953 Israel’s First International Exhibition Closes; Visited by 600,000|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref>
Thirteen foreign countries participated.<ref name="shanghaiinfo" /> This included the United States, although it declared a boycott of the opening ceremony.<ref name="paperusboycott">{{cite web|url=http://archive.jta.org/article/1953/09/23/3037141/us-explains-its-boycott-of-exhibition-opening |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130415042052/http://archive.jta.org/article/1953/09/23/3037141/us-explains-its-boycott-of-exhibition-opening |dead-url=yes |archive-date=15 April 2013 |title=U.S. Explains Its Boycott of Exhibition Opening |accessdate=13 March 2012 }}</ref> The Soviet Union declined to attend.<ref name="paperrussia">{{cite web|url=http://archive.jta.org/article/1952/08/26/3032971/soviet-declines-invitation-to-participate-in-israel-exhibition|title=Soviet Declines Invitation to Participate in Israel Exhibition|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref> [[UNESCO]] and the [[World Health Organization]] also attended.<ref name="stamp" />
Postage stamps commemorating the exhibition were designed by [[Abram Games]].<ref name="stamp" />
