{{Infobox building | name = Vilnius TV Tower | image = Vilnius TV tower.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = The Vilnius TV Tower | start_date = 1974 | completion_date = 1980 | map_type = Lithuania Vilnius#Lithuania | map_alt = | map_caption = Location within Vilnius | building_type = observation, telecommunications, attraction | location = [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]] | coordinates = {{coord|54|41|14|N|025|12|53|E|region:LT|display=inline,title}} | antenna_spire = {{convert|326.5|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} | roof = | top_floor = | floor_count = | elevator_count = | architect = }}
The '''Vilnius TV Tower''' ({{lang-lt|Vilniaus televizijos bokštas}}) is a {{convert|326.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} [[tower]] in the [[Karoliniškės]] [[microdistrict]] of [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]]. It is the tallest structure in Lithuania, and is occupied by the SC Lithuanian Radio and Television Centre ({{lang-lt|AB Lietuvos radijo ir televizijos centras}}).
==Design and construction== {{stack|[[File:Utsikt over vilnius tv-torn.jpg|thumb|right|View from Vilnius TV tower]]}} The tower was designed by V. Obydovas and the engineering section by K. Balėnas. The construction of the tower started on 31 May 1974 and finished on December 30, 1980. The construction was funded by the 11th Five Year Plan of the Soviet Union, which had earmarked funds for strategic investment in the then Lithuanian SSR. The weight of the whole structure is estimated at {{convert|25000|to(-)|30000|MT|lb}}. The structure is composed of a concrete base, a {{convert|190|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long hollow [[reinforced concrete]] pipe, a reinforced concrete saucer, and a {{convert|136|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} long steel spike. Radio transmitters are housed in the lower part of the concrete tower with antennas attached to the steel spike.
The observation deck {{convert|165|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} from the ground houses the cafe "Paukščių takas" ({{lang-en|[[Milky Way]]}}), offers a picturesque view of the city and its surroundings, and sports a rotating platform that revolves once every 45 minutes. High-speed elevators reach the cafe from ground level in 40 seconds. On clear days, visibility can extend as far as [[Elektrėnai]], a city approximately {{convert|40|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} west, where power plants produced much of the electricity for Vilnius in Soviet times.
==Museum== The TV tower played a major role in the [[Vilnius massacre|events of 13 January 1991]], when 14 unarmed civilians lost their lives and 700 were injured opposing the Soviet military seizure of the tower. A small museum dedicated to the January 1991 battle is housed on the ground floor, and various markers in the surrounding area indicate places where Lithuanian citizens died while trying to maintain the blockade against [[Soviet]] troops. [[File:Decorated Vilnius TV Tower.jpg|thumb|left|Decorated Vilnius TV Tower]]
==Decoration== Since 2000, the tower has been decorated to look like a [[Christmas tree]] each Christmas season. During the [[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006 World Basketball Championship]] it was decorated with a large basketball net. Vilnius TV Tower became [http://www.lithuaniatribune.com/2011/08/05/vilnius-tv-tower-to-become-biggest-basketball-hoop-in-the-world/ the biggest basketball hoop in the world] during the 2011 FIBA European Basketball Championship. The hoop was 35 metres in diameter with a 40&nbsp; metre-high net, assembled at a height of 170&nbsp;metres. The lighting of the giant hoop took 2,560&nbsp;metres of lighting cable and 545 bulbs. [[Bungee jumping|Bungee jumps]] are available to the public from the roof of the observation deck.
